explanation:
To decide whether any operations in OS_ModuleSymbolLookup are dead (i.e., executed but removable without changing observable behaviour) the analyzer needs the definitions/semantics of the symbols that affect control flow, side-effects, and observable outputs:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro may perform an early return, assert, or other side-effects on null pointers. Its semantics determine whether the rest of the function can legally execute and whether the pointer checks are removable.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Controls entry into the main if-block (return_code == OS_SUCCESS). We must know its possible return values and side-effects (e.g., whether it can always fail or always succeed, whether it modifies global state) to determine whether the guarded block is ever executed or is effectively dead.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Used to obtain record from OS_global_module_table and token. Need its behavior to determine whether 'record' is a fresh pointer, an alias into global state, or invalid after token release (affects whether accesses via record are meaningful or removable).

- OS_global_module_table: The underlying data structure used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its lifetime/contents affect whether record->name_entry is valid and whether reading it has observable effect.

- OS_ModuleSymbolLookup_Impl: The low-level lookup sets return_code and (likely) symbol_address. Knowing whether it always succeeds/fails or has important side-effects is required to judge whether the subsequent static lookup or other operations are redundant (dead).

- OS_SymbolLookup_Static: Called when the impl fails. Its semantics (whether it modifies symbol_address or other observable state, whether it ever returns OS_SUCCESS) determine whether that call and its conditional overwrite of return_code are meaningful or removable.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the token; may have side-effects (resource accounting, notifications). Also relevant for pointer lifetime: if record aliases the token-managed resource, release may invalidate record, affecting whether earlier uses were meaningful.

- OS_common_record_t (member: name_entry): The code reads record->name_entry to pass to OS_SymbolLookup_Static. The structure definition (and the semantics of name_entry) determine whether that read is observable or redundant.

- OS_SUCCESS: The numeric value(s) used in comparisons; necessary to reason about conditions and whether branches can be true/false.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type and its semantics (value, ownership, aliasing) are needed to understand aliasing/validity of record and whether operations using the token are required for observable behaviour.

Providing these symbols lets the next analyzer determine if any executed operation (pointer checks, table lookup, impl/static lookups, token release, reads of record->name_entry) can be removed without changing observable behaviour, i.e., whether they are dead code under the MISRA C definition.
